05965nam a22009135i 9789812307279DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20062006si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898123072797 a10.1355/97898123072792doi  a(DE-B1597)492645  a(OCoLC)1042007521  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aHD9502.A782bS564 2006 7aBUS0700402bisacsh04a333.7909522300aSingapore Energy Conference 2006 :bSummary Report /ced. by ISEAS. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (84 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- t1. Energy: A Strategic Necessity -- t2. Developing a Holistic Energy Policy -- t3. Dawn of a New Age: Global Energy Scenarios to 2030 -- t4. Geopolitics of Oil and Gas: Challenges in a Turbulent Oil and Gas Industry -- t5. Regional Outlook on Energy Security: Who Wins in the Asian Scramble for Oil? -- t6. Sustainable Development and Energy Efficiency -- t7. World Energy Outlook -- t8. Prospects for Renewable Energy in Asia and Its Role in Energy Security -- t9. Enhancing Energy Security in Asia: The Role of Governments -- t10. Closing Remarks -- t11. Conclusions -- tConference Programme0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEnergy is a very basic need for the economy and also for civilization. Nothing moves and no machine operates without an energy source, whether it is manpower, animal power, natural (wind, water, solar) or fossil fuels (oil, coal, gas, bio-mass) or scientific/technological (nuclear, ion-drive, fusion). When an adversary cuts off energy supplies, this is clearly a hostile act, and is recognized as such. Thus strategists understood why Imperial Japan reacted in military terms to the U.S. action in imposing an oil embargo on Tokyo. This is also the reason why India and China today are concerned about the security of energy supplies, needed for their booming economies. Energy security has thus moved to the top of the international and national agendas. It is therefore very timely that ISEAS and three government agencies have cooperated to organize and launch the Singapore Energy Conference (SEC). This Summary Report of the Inaugural SEC, held on 8 and 9 November 2006, serves to briefly record the main points of the various presentations and discussions by several energy experts on important energy issues and trends. It signals the commitment by the Government of Singapore to raise awareness and understanding of energy issues amongst policy-makers and others who need to know and understand such issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnergy consumptionzAsiavCongresses. 0aEnergy developmentzAsiavCongresses. 0aPower resourceszAsiavCongresses. 0aRenewable energy sourceszAsiavCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Energy.2bisacsh1 aBurkhard, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChantanakome, Weerawat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHefner, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aISEAS, , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJayakumar, S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKesavapany, K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMandil, Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPachauri, R. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez, Vince, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eB